instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is achieved by coupling a white‑box analytical model (e.g., a Simulink dynamic simulation of the robot mechanics) with a black‑box data‑driven model (e.g., a machine‑learning friction estimator). The combined approach leverages the interpretability of the analytical model and the expressive power of the data‑driven model to capture nonlinear friction phenomena. Validation is performed by comparing simulated outputs against measured sensor traces, using the traceability links provided by the ‘originates‑from’ association to pinpoint sources of deviation. Uncertainty sources include modelling errors in the analytical dynamics and inaccuracies in the sensor data traces; these are quantified through residual analysis between simulated and measured data. Error detection relies on automatic consistency checks of transformation steps (e.g., SysML‑to‑Simulink conversion), and correction mechanisms involve re‑training the data‑driven model or updating model parameters. Overall quality assurance is supported by systematic verification of model transformations and by maintaining full provenance metadata for each data trace and model artifact."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The approach relies on established industry standards. Model‑Based Systems‑Engineering is performed with SysML, an OMG standard modeling language. The Digital Twin is built on the Digital Shadow Reference Model, which defines a conformance relation that precisely identifies the set of conforming models within the same language. Asset Administration Shells (AAS) are employed to encapsulate asset metadata, supporting interoperability in Industry 4.0 environments."
]
